session

Class Client

  • java.lang.Object
    • session.Client

  • public class Client
extends java.lang.Object
    This is the Client class, which will be generated for each connected client that handshakes with the server. It stores both the IP as well as a unique ID. If the ID is not specified, then the client is to send the IP as the ID.

    • Constructor Detail

      • Client

        public Client(java.lang.String clientID,
              java.lang.String IP)
        Client constructor that takes in an ID and IP. The ID is the ID of the client and should be unique. If its the same, the client should be rejected. The IP is also tracking who is connected in order to make sure clients don't change their ID during sessions.
        Parameters:
        clientID - - The Client's unique ID. Should be a string resembling their name, or their IP is they didn't specify.
        IP - - The Client's IP to store to check to make sure that a user isn't changing their name to fake another client

      • setLastVote

        public void setLastVote(Vote newVote)
        Sets the clients most recently sent vote as their current vote. This is used so that when a user votes multiple times during a session, this can be used to remove them from their last vote without having to search through the entire mapping.
        Parameters:
        newVote - - The new vote of the client that has been stored in the mapping

      • setAnswerVote

        public void setAnswerVote(Question q,
                          Vote v)
        UNUSED - When a question is finished this method is to mark the client's final vote for that question and create a mapping from that Question to that Vote.
        Parameters:
        q - - The Question to which the client has just finished voting for.
        v - - The Client's final vote for said question.

      • equals

        public boolean equals(java.lang.Object o)
        Overwrite of the equals method that is to do the same thing, however, it matches clients based on IP. Thusly, if multiple clients have the same IP (which should never happen) and different ID's, they will still return equal.
        Overrides:
        equals in class java.lang.Object
        Returns:
        True if the IP sent in matches the current client's IP. False if the IPs don't match
